genealogy and using that ancestor as the sole basis for an eventual shift into an “Indigenous” identity today. After setting out the most common genealogical practices that facilitate race shifting, Leroux examines two of the most prominent self-identified “Indigenous” organizations currently operating in Quebec. Both organizations have their origins in committed opposition to Indigenous land and territorial negotiations, and both encourage the use of suspect genealogical practices. Distorted Descent brings to light to how these claims to an “Indigenous” identity are then used politically to oppose actual, living Indigenous peoples, exposing along the way the shifting politics of whiteness, white settler colonialism, and white supremacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGenealogyxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province) 0aGenealogyxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province). 0aMétiszQuébec (Province) 0aMétiszQuébec (Province). 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzQuébec (Province) 0aWhite peoplezQuébec (Province)xGenealogy. 0aWhitesxRace identityzQuébec (Province). 0aWhiteszQuébec (Province)xGenealogy. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755596140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555961/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles